\pard\sa120 {\f0 \cf1 \fs52 Demonstration of DOCX support in calibre}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 This document demonstrates the ability of the calibre DOCX Input plugin to convert the various typographic features in a Microsoft Word (2007 and newer) document. Convert this document to a modern ebook format, such as AZW3 for Kindles or EPUB for other ebook readers, to see it in action.}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 There is support for images, tables, lists, footnotes, endnotes, links, dropcaps and various types of text and paragraph level formatting.}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 To see the DOCX conversion in action, simply add this file to calibre using the }{\f0 \b \fs24 {\uc0\u8220}Add Books{\uc0\u8221} \b0 }{\f0 \fs24 button and then click {\uc0\u8220}}{\f0 \b \fs24 Convert{\uc0\u8221}. \b0 }{\f0 \fs24  Set the output format in the top right corner of the conversion dialog to EPUB or AZW3 and click }{\f0 \b \fs24 {\uc0\u8220}OK{\uc0\u8221}\b0 }{\f0 \fs24 .}\par
\pard\s1\sb240\sa120{\b\fs44 {\f0 \b \cf2 \fs28 Text Formatting\b0 }}\par
\pard\s2\sb240\sa120{\b\fs40 {\f0 \b \cf3 \fs26 Inline formatting\b0 }}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 Here, we demonstrate various types of inline text formatting and the use of embedded fonts.}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 Here is some }{\f0 \b \fs24 bold, \b0 }{\f0 \i \fs24 italic, \i0 }{\f0 \b \i \fs24 bold-italic, \i0 \b0 }{\f0 \ul \fs24 underlined \ul0 }{\f0 \fs24 and }{\f0 \strike \fs24 struck out \strike0 }{\f0 \fs24  text. Then, we have a super}{\f0 \fs24 script}{\f0 \fs24  and a sub}{\f0 \fs24 script}{\f0 \fs24 . Now we see some }{\f0 \cf4 \fs24 red}{\f0 \fs24 , }{\f0 \cf5 \fs24 green}{\f0 \fs24  and }{\f0 \cf6 \fs24 blue}{\f0 \fs24  text. Some text with a }{\f0 \highlight7 \fs24 yellow highlight}{\f0 \fs24 . Some text in a box. Some text in }{\f0 \cf8 \highlight9 \fs24 inverse video}{\f0 \fs24 .}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 A paragraph with styled text: }{\f0 \i \cf10 \fs24 subtle emphasis  \i0 }{\f0 \fs24 followed by }{\f0 \b \fs24 strong text \b0 }{\f0 \fs24 and }{\f0 \b \i \cf3 \fs24 intense emphasis\i0 \b0 }{\f0 \fs24 . This paragraph uses document wide styles for styling rather than inline text properties as demonstrated in the previous paragraph  calibre can handle both with equal ease.}\par
\pard\s2\sb240\sa120{\b\fs40 {\f0 \b \cf3 \fs26 Fun with fonts\b0 }}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 This document has embedded the Ubuntu font family. The body text is in the Ubuntu typeface, here is }{\f0 \fs24 some text in the Ubuntu Mono typeface, notice how every letter has the same width, even i and m}{\f0 \fs24 . Every embedded font will automatically be embedded in the output ebook during conversion. }\par
\pard\s2\sb240\sa120{\b\fs40 {\f0 \b \cf3 \fs26 Paragraph level formatting\b0 }}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \highlight11 \fs24 You can do crazy things with paragraphs, if the urge strikes you. For instance this paragraph is right aligned and has a right border. It has also been given a light gray background.}\par
\pard\sa120 {\f0 \fs24 For the lovers of poetry amongst you, paragraphs with hanging indents, like this often come in handy. You can use hanging indents to ensure that a line of poetry retains its individual identity as a line even when the screen is  too narrow to display it as a single line. Not only does this paragraph have a hanging indent, it is also has an extra top margin, setting it apart from the preceding paragraph.}\par
